sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE COME OUT ON TOP AFTER WINNING THE INNINGS.
West Indian all-rounder Phil Simmons scored four for 38 on Friday as Leicestershire beat Somerset by an innings and 39 runs in two days to take the lead in the county championship.
However, their stay at the top may be short-lived as title rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey came close to victory, while Kent made up for lost time in a rain-affected game against Nottinghamshire.

After bowling Somerset out for 83 on the opening morning at Grace Road, Leicestershire extended their first innings by 94 runs before they were bowled out for 296 with England discard Andy Caddick taking three for 83.
Somerset, trailing by 213 points, started their second inning solidly until Simmons stepped in to shut them out for 174 points.
Essex, however, are certain to wrestle back top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such firmly dominated the game against Yorkshire at Headingley.
Hussain, who is considered surplus to England's one-day requirements, struck 158, his first masterful century of the season, as Essex reached 372 and took a first innings lead of 82.
In the end Yorkshire converted this into a 37-run advantage but off-spinner Such dashed their hopes, taking four for 24 in 48 balls and leaving them hanging on at 119 for five and praying for rain.

At The Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another man dropped by England, continued to silence his critics as he followed up his four for 45 on Thursday with 80 not out in Friday's match against Warwickshire.
He was well supported by England hopeful Mark Butcher, who scored 70 points as Surrey closed on 429 points, a lead of 234 points.
Derbyshire continued the chase for their first championship title since 1936 by reducing Worcestershire to 133 for five in their second innings, still 100 runs away from avoiding an innings defeat.
Australian Tom Moody scored six points for 82, but Chris Adams, 123, and Tim O'Gorman, 109, led Derbyshire to 471 points and a first-round lead of 233.
After the frustration of having the opening day of their match heavily affected by the weather, Kent stepped up a gear and dismissed Nottinghamshire for 214.
Paul Johnson held them to 84 points, but former England fast bowler Martin McCague scored four for 55 points.

The world's most expensive footballer, Alan Shearer, was appointed England's new captain on Friday.
The twenty-six-year-old, who arrived at Newcastle for 15 million pounds ($23.4 million), replaces Tony Adams, who led the team during June's European championship, and former captain David Platt.
Adams and Platt are injured and will miss England's opening game of World Cup qualifying against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer took over the captaincy on trial, but new coach Glenn Hoddle said he saw no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton captain should not become captain.
"I'm sure it won't be a problem, I'm sure Alan is the man in the right place," Hoddle said.
"There were three or four people who could have done it, but when I spoke to Alan, he was up for it and really wanted to do it.
"It's very difficult to come to a hundred percent conclusion about something like this in four days...
but he knows how to behave, his teammates respect him and he knows about the situation in the team, even when he plays up front. "
Shearer's Euro 96 partner Teddy Sheringham withdrew from the team on Friday due to injury.
He is likely to be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle teammate Les Ferdinand.

FOOTBALL - ROTOR FANS LOCKED OUT AFTER VIOLENCE IN VOLGOGRAD.

Rotor Volgograd must play its next home game behind closed doors after fans threw bottles and stones at Dynamo Moscow players during Saturday's 1-0 home loss that ended Rotor's brief period at the top of the league.
Anatoly Gorokhovsky, head of the Russian league's disciplinary commission, said Friday that Rotor will play Lada Togliatti in front of empty stands on Sept. 3.
The club, which knocked Manchester United out of last year's UEFA Cup, was fined $1,000.
Despite the defeat, Rotor is in a good position with 11 games left to play in the championship.
The Volgograd team are three points behind Alania and two behind Dinamo Moscow, with a game to spare over the leaders and two ahead of the Moscow club.
BOXING - PANAMA'S ROBERTO DURAN FIGHTS THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Hands of Stone" Duran will step into the ring on Saturday in another attempt to keep his long career alive.
The 45-year-old Duran will face little-known 30-year-old Mexican Ariel Cruz in Panama City in a non-title super middleweight bout.
The match, Duran's first on home soil in a decade, is being billed here as "the return of a legend" and Duran still talks as if he's in his prime.
This match is to prepare me.
I'm not retiring," Duran told Reuters.

However, those close to the boxer acknowledge that the man who has won championships in four different weight classes - lightweight, welterweight, junior welterweight and middleweight - is nearing the end of his career.
"With every game, he's on the final frontier of his career.
If he loses on Saturday, it could devalue his position as one of the world's best boxers," said Panama Boxing Association President Ramon Manzanares.
Duran, whose 97-12 record spans three decades, hopes a win in the 10-round bout will earn him a rematch against Puerto Rico's Hector "Macho" Camacho.
Camacho controversially lost a controversial decision on points to the Panamanian in a title fight in Atlantic City in June.

TENNIS - TARANGO, O'BRIEN UNDER LIGHTS LOST.
Andre Agassi escaped disaster on Thursday, but Wimbledon finalist MaliVai Washington and Marcelo Rios weren't so lucky during a night full of twists and turns at the US Open.
The 11th-seeded Washington player couldn't repeat his Wimbledon miracle, losing to hot wild card Alex O'Brien 6-3 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 in a two-hour and 51-minute match on the Stadium Court.
Next on the grandstand, tenth-seeded Rios lost to another player with a Wimbledon past - bad boy Jeff Tarang.
The temperamental left-hander beat the Chilean 6-4 4-6 7-6 6-2.
The day's programme went smoothly, although sixth-seeded former champion Agassi had to dig himself out of a dangerous 3:6, 0:4 deficit to win 18 of the last 19 games against India's Leander Paes.
The night, however, belonged to the newcomers.
Washington, who came from a 1-5 deficit in the Wimbledon semifinals against Todd Martin to trail by two sets in the third set, looked poised for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, who won his first professional title two weeks ago in New Haven, served for the win at 5-4 in the third set before Washington faltered.
"I kept telling myself, 'Give yourself the best chance to win, keep fighting, maybe something will happen,'" said the 26-year-old O'Brien, who is ranked 65th in the rankings.
"I kept calm and was proud of myself - normally I would have folded up my tent and gone home."
The tough O'Brien, a former American University champion, fired 17 aces to finally beat the indomitable Washington.
The fifth set remained on serve until the sixth game when Washington, after saving one break point with a forehand winner down the line, played a backhand into the net to put O'Brien up 4:2.
The Texan held serve with two aces to make it 5-2 and then converted his eighth match point for the win when Washington found the net with another backhand from 40-0.
"You're just trying to fight and make him play.
I think he tightened up a little bit at some points," Washington said.
But I think he served quite well when he had to. "

Tarango, whose Wimbledon tantrum two years ago earned him a $28,000 fine and expulsion from this year's tournament at the All-England Club, argued with and taunted fans during his lively two-hour, 24-minute tango with Rios in the stands.
The raucous cheering supported the distracted Chilean and booed the lanky American, who drew all the attention to himself.
"I'm an emotional player," said the 104th-ranked Tarango player. "
I think I played very well today, very focused. "
The match was decided in the third set tiebreak, which the American won 7:5, much to the dismay of the spectators.
"I love the audience, even if they boo me every day.
It will kick-start me and make me play my best tennis," Tarango said.
"I played my best tennis in college when fraternities doused me with beer.
If tennis was like this every day, I think everyone would have a lot more fun. "
"He always complains too much," Rios said. "
But I don't think that's the case.
I think I played really badly.
It was hard to play at night.
The balls were flying very fast.
I've lost too many points that I will never lose.
"I don't see the ball like I do during the day.
I'm playing an American, that's why I play at night.
I didn't feel good on the court. "
At the end of the match, Tarango sarcastically kissed the crowd and then swayed his body to Rios' fan section, who mockingly gave him a tribute.
"I support their enthusiasm," Tarango said of the fans. "
At the same time, they blatantly cheer against me.
After I won, I figured I could give them a little pizzazz. "
NFL AMERICAN FOOTBALL - RANDALL CUNNINGHAM RETIRES.
Randall Cunningham, the National Football League's best quarterback and one of the most athletic players ever to play the center position, retired Thursday.
Cunningham played his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
Cunningham, who was selected to the Pro Bowl three times, rushed for 4,482 yards on 677 carries.
"I would like to thank the Eagles organization and the great Philadelphia fans for their support throughout my career," Cunningham said.
"Although I'm sad to leave, I'm looking forward to being able to spend more time with my family and pursue other interests that have been on the back burner for some time."
"Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie said. "
During his 11 years in Philadelphia, Randall was a cornerstone of the Eagles franchise and brought many great moments to fans in Philadelphia, as well as throughout the NFL. "
In 1985, Cunningham was selected in the second round of the draft, completing 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7%) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has already signed a contract as a broadcaster.
